itions, adultery, homosexuality, and the demands of individual identity. Each is accompanied by an essay, in which Lauro Martines situates the story in its temporal context, transforming it into an outright historical document. The stories and essays focus mainly on people from the ordinary and middling ranks of society, as they go about their ordinary lives, under the pressure of a highly practical, conformist, pleasure-loving (but often cruel) urban society. Revealing the concerns of a searching historical work with a combined anthropological, demographic, and cultural slant, An Italian Renaissance Sextet shines a probing light on Italian Renaissance culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh1 aBaca, Murtha.1 aManetti, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMedici, Lorenzo de\x27, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrato, Giovanni Gherardi da, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSermini, Gentile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVeneziano, Piero, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267081540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442670815423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442670815.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK